{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"180b282f-e904-40d1-a409-a5622465b27b","content":"You can install `dotnet-trace` as a standalone tool without the SDK using the **dotnet-install script** or by downloading it directly:\n\n**Option 1 – Download the global tool standalone (no SDK needed):**\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Option 2 – Copy into running container from host:**\n```bash\n# On host with SDK\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\ndocker cp ~/.dotnet/tools/dotnet-trace <container>:/tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Then collect the CPU trace:**\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).\n\n> **Tip:** If you also need to collect GC or allocation data, swap `cpu-sampling` for `gc-collect` or use `--providers` to specify custom EventPipe providers.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"430731e3-271d-45ed-8b98-f1e64090f65f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU. This is a practical DevOps/diagnostics question.\n\nLet me give a concise, helpful answer based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics tooling.","outputTokens":376,"requestId":"784E:A067E:1C82B3E:1FD4F69:69FA9919"},"id":"cfedb89a-d337-427b-b660-0bb56149921c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:28:03.021Z","parentId":"fceec8dd-77d1-45b4-a117-9d18db66b53d"}
